sfwLiteral.Text: Please review these documents before continuing with the application process:

sfwLabel.Text:
Before you begin your application, read the following:
• Your application must be on file for one full month (31 days) prior to payment.
• Benefit payments are only issued on the first working day of the month.
• Your employer must confirm your termination date to NDPERS.
• Your payment will be issued in approximately 60 to 90 days, subject to tax notification requirements.
• You may not return to an NDPERS-covered Employer prior to receiving your refund or direct rollover.
Please review the appropriate handbook prior to selecting your refund options:
You must enter a valid email address before you begin.
The email address used will authorize NDPERS to send you future notifications.

For a rollover of all or a portion of your retirement account, you will need:
If you transfer or return to work with a NDPERS participating employer prior to distribution, you are not eligible for a refund/rollover and your application will be cancelled.

If you have service with the Teachers Fund for Retirement (TFFR) or the ND University System TIAA retirement plans, contact NDPERS regarding dual membership options by emailing ndpers-info@nd.gov.

If you have service credit in multiple NDPERS plans (Main, Public Safety, Judges, Highway Patrol), contact NDPERS regarding dual membership options by emailing ndpers-info@nd.gov.

Prior to starting your retirement, you will need:
Your application must be on file at least 31 days before distribution of your first retirement check. Your earliest NDPERS retirement effective date will be the first of the month following your last date worked or last paycheck issued, whichever is later. Retiree insurance coverage begins the 1st of the month that your first check is issued.

•If you have service with the Teachers Fund for Retirement (TFFR) or the ND University System TIAA retirement plans, contact NDPERS regarding dual membership options by emailing ndpers-info@nd.gov.

•If you have service credit in multiple NDPERS plans (Main, Public Safety, Judges, Highway Patrol), contact NDPERS regarding dual membership options by emailing ndpers-info@nd.gov.

When entering a Percentage the total has to equal 100% or you may enter a Flat Amount on one of the accounts and the remaining benefit payment will be deposited to the second. Federal income tax, at the rate of 20%, will be withheld from the taxable portion of your refund. ND state income tax, at the rate 3.92%, will be automatically withheld
from taxable portion of your refund unless indicated below.
After a refund check is issued, any adjustments to Federal or State income tax paid is the responsibility of the taxpayer.

For income tax purposes, the amount of withholding is based on the marital status and the number of allowances (including zero) you indicate. </br> If you wish to change your income tax election, please complete the Marital Status, Tax Allowance, and Tax Option fields.</br> If you select the Tax Option of “Based on IRS Table and Additional Tax” you must also complete the Additional Tax Amount field.</br> The additional tax amount will be added to the calculated income tax based on your Marital Status and Tax Allowance.

Monthly amount to withhold for North Dakota State Tax :
Your withholding rate is determined by the type of payment you will receive.

• For Required Minimum Distributions (RMDs), the default withholding rate is 10%. You can choose to have a different rate by entering a rate between 0% and 100% by submitting a W-4R. Generally, you can’t choose less than 10% for payments to be delivered outside the United States and its possessions.
• For the taxable portion of your distribution, the default withholding rate is 20%. You can choose a rate greater than 20% by submitting the W-4R. You may not choose a rate less than 20%.
If you would like a rate of withholding that is different from the default withholding rate, please complete the IRS Form W-4R and upload or mail to NDPERS.
